author: @LukeBarousse
text: Updates for Video üëá =========================================================================== 2:06:55 - Database Load Issues  WATCH THIS VIDEO FOR A WALKTHROUGH OF THESE INSTRUCTIONS: https://lukeb.co/sql_error  NOTE: If you are having issues with permissions. And you get an error like: "could not open file "C:\file_path\job_postings_fact.csv" for reading: Permission denied."  1. Open pgAdmin  2. In Object Explorer (left-hand pane), navigate to `sql_course` database  3. Right-click `sql_course` and select `PSQL Tool`         - This opens a terminal window to write the following code  4. Get the absolute file path of your csv files         a. Find path by right-clicking a CSV file in VS Code and selecting ‚ÄúCopy Path‚Äù  5. Paste the following into `PSQL Tool`, (with the CORRECT file path)         \copy company_dim FROM '[Insert File Path]/company_dim.csv' WITH (FORMAT csv, HEADER true, DELIMITER ',', ENCODING 'UTF8');  \copy skills_dim FROM '[Insert File Path]/skills_dim.csv' WITH (FORMAT csv, HEADER true, DELIMITER ',', ENCODING 'UTF8');  \copy job_postings_fact FROM '[Insert File Path]/job_postings_fact.csv' WITH (FORMAT csv, HEADER true, DELIMITER ',', ENCODING 'UTF8');  \copy skills_job_dim FROM '[Insert File Path]/skills_job_dim.csv' WITH (FORMAT csv, HEADER true, DELIMITER ',', ENCODING 'UTF8');  =========================================================================== 2:06:55 - Duplicate Key Error  NOTE: If you are getting the following error (below) even after following the steps above you need to restart over and drop the database: ERROR >>  duplicate key value violates unique constraint "company_dim_pkey" ERROR >> could not open file "C:\Users\...\company_dim.csv" for reading: Permission denied  1. Drop the Database              DROP DATABASE IF EXISTS sql_course;  2. Repeat steps to create database and load table schemas  3. Follow steps above for copying CSV files into the sql_course database  =========================================================================== 3:08:15 Git Error  - "Tell me who you are"  NOTE: Some users, setting up git for the first time are receiving the following error:  Please tell me who you are. Run git config --global user.email "you@example.com" git config --global user.name "Your Name"  1. Open your terminal. 2. Set your Git identity by :           git config --global user.email "[insert email address]"           git config --global user.name "[insert your name]" 3. Continue video

author: @anastasiosvra9024
text: Hi Luke! Thanks for the great content! I got a question as I approach toward the end of this video. I need an explanation on why even though the group by clause does not contain the column "skills", the query works normally without any errors in postgre sql. I know that whatever is in the select statement besides aggregate functions, must be in the group by statement too. ChatGPT  gave me some insights on this like "In PostgreSQL and some other database systems, there's a feature called "functional dependency" or "functional determinant" that can allow a query to execute successfully even if the GROUP BY clause does not explicitly include all non-aggregated columns from the SELECT clause".  I do get the understanding that even if this works here because "each unique skill_id corresponds to only one skills value" , this is something to be avoided when querying databases as it is likely to give us back an error. Please provide some feedback!   Thanks so much Man

author: @LukeBarousse
text: Updates for Video üëá =========================================================================== 2:06:55 - Database Load Issues  WATCH THIS VIDEO FOR A WALKTHROUGH OF THESE INSTRUCTIONS: https://lukeb.co/sql_error  NOTE: If you are having issues with permissions. And you get an error like: "could not open file "C:\file_path\job_postings_fact.csv" for reading: Permission denied."  1. Open pgAdmin  2. In Object Explorer (left-hand pane), navigate to `sql_course` database  3. Right-click `sql_course` and select `PSQL Tool`         - This opens a terminal window to write the following code  4. Get the absolute file path of your csv files         a. Find path by right-clicking a CSV file in VS Code and selecting ‚ÄúCopy Path‚Äù  5. Paste the following into `PSQL Tool`, (with the CORRECT file path)         \copy company_dim FROM '[Insert File Path]/company_dim.csv' WITH (FORMAT csv, HEADER true, DELIMITER ',', ENCODING 'UTF8');  \copy skills_dim FROM '[Insert File Path]/skills_dim.csv' WITH (FORMAT csv, HEADER true, DELIMITER ',', ENCODING 'UTF8');  \copy job_postings_fact FROM '[Insert File Path]/job_postings_fact.csv' WITH (FORMAT csv, HEADER true, DELIMITER ',', ENCODING 'UTF8');  \copy skills_job_dim FROM '[Insert File Path]/skills_job_dim.csv' WITH (FORMAT csv, HEADER true, DELIMITER ',', ENCODING 'UTF8');  =========================================================================== 2:06:55 - Duplicate Key Error  NOTE: If you are getting the following error (below) even after following the steps above you need to restart over and drop the database: ERROR >>  duplicate key value violates unique constraint "company_dim_pkey" ERROR >> could not open file "C:\Users\...\company_dim.csv" for reading: Permission denied  1. Drop the Database              DROP DATABASE IF EXISTS sql_course;  2. Repeat steps to create database and load table schemas  3. Follow steps above for copying CSV files into the sql_course database  =========================================================================== 3:08:15 Git Error  - "Tell me who you are"  NOTE: Some users, setting up git for the first time are receiving the following error:  Please tell me who you are. Run git config --global user.email "you@example.com" git config --global user.name "Your Name"  1. Open your terminal. 2. Set your Git identity by :           git config --global user.email "[insert email address]"           git config --global user.name "[insert your name]" 3. Continue video

author: @SwapnilDeore-ts2kx
text: To all my Data peeps if you are stuck at 2:09:40 where we are loading our datasets into our sql_course database for PostgreSQL you will get an error which looks like this:  could not open file "xxxxxxxxxxxxx.csv" for reading: Permission denied  To solve this (I am a windows user) follow my steps:  1. Go to your program files where you have installed your postgresSQL. 2. Program Files > PostgreSQL > 16 > data > (Now, you are inside the data folder. I recommend you to create a new folder called Datasets) >  ("Inside the Datasets folder you can keep creating new folders for your different projects"). 3. In your code editor or pgAdmin (whatever you are using) change your code. It should look something like this:  COPY company_dim FROM 'C:/Program Files/PostgreSQL/16/data/Datasets/sql_course/company_dim.csv' DELIMITER ',' CSV HEADER;   4. Do it for all others. Your data will be loaded successfully.  Happy learning to all!üòÑ

author: @jimcallahan448
text: Looks good. Made perfect sense to me, but I am concerned about beginners. Fortunately you keep saying "we will come back to this later", if beginners can set aside panic, this should be a very rapid, but thorough introduction to SQL. Future versions may want to mention a path from SQLite to DuckDB. Although SQLite is standard now, DuckDB has targeted analytic workloads (CSV) as opposed to transactional workloads (forms). DuckDB SQL is also closer to Postgres SQL (built with Postgres interpreter). DuckDB has amazingly fast loading of CSV files and SQL SELECT queries!
